Is there some special logic, which causes this? Or is it a reference by value issue, so that I only modify the `Jupyter` object I have in the extension, but not the actual one?

Currently asyncio doesn't support test methods (see #4):

```python
class Test:
    @pytest.mark.asyncio
    def test_some_asyncio_code(self):
        res = yield from library.do_something()
        assert b'expected result' == res
```

Hi,

When a file cannot be access because it's used by another process, or when a file cannot be created because it already exists, the System.IO.File Open function throws an IOException with an invalid HResult value.

Sample code below returns 11 (EAGAIN?) instead of -2147024864 (ERROR_SHARING_VIOLATION). For a file in use it returns 17 (EEXIST?) instead of -2147024816 (ERROR_FILE_EXISTS). 

Since HResult is ok for a file not found (-2147024894 correspond to ERROR_FILE_NOT_FOUND) , it seems there is some missing mapping for conversion between Linux error code and Windows error code.


| Test | HResult on Windows | HResult on Linux | Result  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| File in use | -2147024864 | 11 | Invalid |
| File already exists | -2147024816 | 17 | Invalid |
| File not found | -2147024894 | -2147024894 | Correct |


This problem is reproductible with dotnet core 2.0 running on an Ubuntu 16.04


# Code sample

```c#
using System;
using System.IO;

namespace FileInUseException
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            var file = @"locked.bin";
            using (File.Create(file))
            {
                Console.WriteLine("=== File in use");
                try
                {
                    File.OpenRead(file);
                    Console.WriteLine("No exception! Weird...");
                }
                catch (IOException ex)
                {
                    Console.WriteLine($"Get an IOException with code {ex.HResult}, message {ex.Message}");
                }
            }

            Console.WriteLine("\n=== File already exists");
            try
            {
                File.Open(file, FileMode.CreateNew, FileAccess.ReadWrite);
                Console.WriteLine("No exception! Weird...");
            }
            catch (IOException ex)
            {
                Console.WriteLine($"Get an IOException with code {ex.HResult}, message {ex.Message}");
            }


            Console.WriteLine("\n=== File not found");
            try
            {
                File.OpenRead("Not Here.bin");
            }
            catch (IOException ex)
            {
                Console.WriteLine($"Get an IOException with code {ex.HResult}, message {ex.Message}");
            }
        }
    }
}
```

